<font color="#FF0000">REVISITING THE FUTURE</font><br>
<tt>Mon Oct 13 11:30:47 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
Art;<br>
You mentioned, &quot;How do you heal something when the cure is long since departed. This is 1997, not 1970. How do you turn back the clock to capture something you needed back then, in the context of back then, in the frame of mind back then, when you and the world have now irrevocably changed into something else.&quot;<br><br>
I personally in order to deal with closure have had to revisit my time and era in Vietnam and what followed. I believe we cannot address the issue psychologically nor can it be adequately addressed with todays historical views of the war. <br><br>
The popular phrase among vets has become, &quot;Welcome Home,&quot; which I hadn't heard until this year. What does that mean? Is it suppose to be the welcome home we never received or a cry of awarness and recognition among vets? <br><br>
I have mentioned before that I feel as if I had been pinned down behind a rice paddy dike all those years, so the war issues were never addresed, many of us have never taken the time to think through much of what transpired at that time. The issues therefore are still fresh because they were never addressed.<br><br>
My reunion with those I served with was I found very needful, it gave me and others the time to reflect upon those common times and to once again embrace that friendship born under the chaos of war which both tore us apart but also made us one. <br><br>
A visit to the wall was also a first step toward reflextion.<br>
I had a chance to visit that wall for the first time a few years back and it had a profound effect on me. The tears I never shed in war, the love I never gave, the moments lost and pains and sorrows shared were all bottled up and released on that day. All Viet Nam veterans should experience such a healing and finally make peace with the past and move on toward the future.... 
<p><code>-- cookbarela@iname.com  (Sparrowhawk) </code><p>


